A Christmas Carol 2019	Abusive Parents	Scrooge's father, who beheads his son's pet mouse and gives Scrooge away to be molested by a schoolmaster.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Age Lift	Scrooge and Marley, usually depicted as elderly men, are played by 52-year-old Guy Pearce and 46-year-old Stephen Graham respectively.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Adaptational Angst Upgrade	Scrooge's childhood is made much, much worse in this version.  His father, rather than just being distant and leaving him at boarding school, is aggressively abusive. His worst acts include beheading a pet mouse Scrooge's sister gave him for a Christmas present and arranging for Scrooge to be molested by the headmaster of the boarding school in exchange for waiving tuition fees.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Adaptational Badass	Most characters, for better or worse.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Adaptation Expansion	The series expands many previously unexplored plot points from the novella such as Jacob Marley's path through the afterlife and subsequent "recruitment" as a harbinger for the Spirits, to Scrooge's time at the boarding school, to Mary Cratchit's expanded role in the story.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Adaptational Name Change	Scrooge's sister, while typically named Fan, is named Lottie in this adaptation.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Adaptational Villainy	
A Christmas Carol 2019	Adapted Out	
A Christmas Carol 2019	Ascended Extra	
A Christmas Carol 2019	Cool Big Sis	Lottie Scrooge, who  pulls a gun on Scrooge's schoolmaster when the latter refuses to let him go home for Christmas.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Covers Always Lie	The promotional image depicts Scrooge with the Ghost of Christmas Future in his traditional visage - the Grim Reaper - hovering ominously behind him. In the actual movie, the Ghost of Christmas Future looks nothing like this, instead, he looks like an eerie gothic man with his lips sewn shut.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Darker and Edgier	Extremely so. This version amps up Scrooge's cruelty to a degree that it nears the Moral Event Horizon, gives him a horrendously tragic past, and cuts out almost all of the original story's lighthearted moments.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Deadpan Snarker	Scrooge, as usual. For instance, responding to Bob Cratchit's "Sort of Christmas present, is it?" (when Scrooge lets him use his ink) with "If it were, I would have wrapped it in paper and ribbons in order to artificially increase your anticipation."
A Christmas Carol 2019	Demoted to Extra	
A Christmas Carol 2019	Dropping the Bombshell	After discovering that Scrooge never intended to have sex with her, Mrs. Cratchit curses him in a way that indicates her involvement with Scrooge's haunting.  "I will... and I will say a prayer, that someday, some power of justice will grab you by the throat and drag you to a true, bright mirror that you might see the truth in your reflection and that the truth will be known to the world. I am a woman, and I have the power to summon such spirits... and I fucking will".
A Christmas Carol 2019	The Ending Changes Everything	The ending suggests the ghosts themselves were actually instruments of Mrs. Cratchit's curse towards Scrooge for sexually exploiting her.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Ethnic Magician	Mary is given a Race Lift and is not only aware of the Spirits but heavily implied to have summoned them.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Freudian Excuse Is No Excuse	While The Ghost of Christmas Past is sympathetic to Ebenezer for what he went through, he still tells him that his history of abuse doesn't excuse his abuse towards others.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Horrifying the Horror	The Ghost of Christmas Past is initially confident that he alone can convince Scrooge to repent as he has done for thousands of other sinful souls, but upon seeing for himself the mental gymnastics that Scrooge is willing to leap through to justify even his most heinous actions appear to send the formidable spirit into a Despair Event Horizon, now convinced as Marley was that there is no hope for Scrooge.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Irony	The legend of Icarus is a story for Tiny Tim and Scrooge references it in a final conversation with him, stating Tiny Tim will learn how to fly. Icarus is famous for flying too close to the sun and plunging to his death after the heat melts the adhesive wax on his wings.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Jerkass Has a Point	Scrooge, despite his many, many shortcomings, does make the good point that people should be kind to each other all year round, rather than just on Christmas Day. His other monologues and soliloquies about the more minor hypocrisies and meaningless trivialities brought upon by the holiday are also hard to dispute.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Love Redeems	Subverted;  The Ghost of Christmas Past shows Scrooge the love of his life and explains to him how Scrooge could have redeemed himself or had a better life if he chose to raise a family instead of work for material gain. Scrooge, while clearly touched by the life he could have had, doesn't see it as a compelling reason to change his current course.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Magical Negro	Twice;
A Christmas Carol 2019	Mouth Stitched Shut	As mortals are not supposed to know too much of their future, the Ghost of Christmas Future's mouth is sewn shut.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Moving the Goalposts	Scrooge frequently describes himself as a man of reason, yet when confronted with something that explicitly contradicts the principles he claims to espouse, he comes up with arguments to reframe either the event or his own principles. His tone of voice when he does so suggests even he finds his own arguments unconvincing.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Not His Sled	The entire Ghost of Christmas Future segment plays out very differently to the original book. First, Tiny Tim's death is shown to be caused not by illness but by falling through the icy lake he was skating on that Christmas afternoon. Next, when faced with the corpse on the bed, Scrooge peels the sheet back to see that it is himself. Then, when he sees his grave being treated the same as Marley's, in a quiet moment with his deceased partner he admits that he doesn't want redemption as he doesn't deserve it and that the only thing he wants to change is Tiny Tim's fate (which he gets to do himself by spreading salt on the lake and making sure Tiny Tim goes nowhere near it). Evidently, this is enough for the powers that be as Marley is shown to receive the peace he was promised at the start of the miniseries for getting Scrooge to change.
A Christmas Carol 2019	O.O.C. Is Serious Business	While the Ghost of Christmas Past's efforts clearly rattle him, they don't actually induce much of a change in his outlook or behaviour. The first time he breaks old habits (not noticing and counting tangible, material things in a room, actually expressing a desire to counteract his previous transgressions rather than engage in mental gymnastics to justify them) is when the Ghost of Christmas Present shows him the Cratchits' home.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Pet the Dog	Almost literally. Even at his worst, Scrooge has a soft spot for animals and it's this, plus an act of kindness to two cold horses, that convinces the powers that be that there is some good worth saving in the man.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Pimping the Offspring	As its revealed in this adaptation, whilst he was a boy Ebenezer Scrooge's father worked out a deal with the pedophilic headmaster of his boarding school that he was free to abuse Scrooge in exchange for his father not having to pay his fees to attend the school.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Race Lift	Mrs. Cratchit is played by black actress Vinette Robinson while most adaptations portray her as white.
A Christmas Carol 2019	"The Reason You Suck" Speech	Mary gives a massive one to Scrooge after  he makes her strip to her undergarments to see how far she would go to save her son's life.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Redemption Rejection	Scrooge attempts this near the end, declaring that he doesn't deserve to be redeemed, and refuses to repent for his own sake. However, his earnest wish that he could save Tiny Tim's life (a truly unselfish action) is enough to convince the spirits that he deserves another chance.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Rewatch Bonus	The feminist theme changes the interaction with The Ghost of Christmas Past; when Scrooge's sister saves him from the boarding school by holding the headmaster at gunpoint, it's initially portrayed as if the ghost is showing how much his family actually loved him. With the ending in mind; the scene changes into the ghost shaming him for becoming just as bad as his headmaster for sexually extorting Mrs. Cratchit, despite being in a similar situation when he was a child.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Scarpia Ultimatum	Scrooge's "experiment". He offers to provide money to Mary Cratchit to save Tim's life if she agrees to give up her virtue. He stops her after she's half-undressed, not being interested in actually having sex with anyone, but he is satisfied that she is willing to humiliate herself for the sake of her son.  She was not happy, and indeed his putting her through this ordeal may have been the reason that Scrooge encountered the ghosts in the first place.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Servile Snarker	This version of Bob Cratchit politely, but assertively, points out when Scrooge is doing things that don't make sense, and he engages in some thinly veiled insults about what a dick he is in general. Scrooge tolerates it either due to Cratchit's extreme competence being profitable for him (which he tells Mary when he  blackmails her into ensuring that Bob doesn't leave his employ) or because Scrooge actually enjoys the slight sparring with somebody who can't risk truly challenging him.
A Christmas Carol 2019	There Are No Therapists	Justified since this is set in the Victorian Era; Scrooge has deep-rooted mental scars after being sexually exploited by his father and repeatedly molested by his headmaster. He was so traumatised that he couldn't recognise how his sister rescued him from the boarding school after the death of his father.
A Christmas Carol 2019	Twisted Christmas	Noticing a theme here? This is quite possibly the darkest take on the story, and certainly a leading contender for it.
